reviewText:
Great just like the two previous games. Matt Bozon & co. simply know what they're doing and that's that.

Pros:
- Quality action/adventure in the vein of Metroid (in a cartoonish 1001 Nights-inspired setting);
- Tight controls;
- Nice difficulty curve (difficulty is only average, but the ramping up difficulty felt properly satisfying to me);
- Great art and character animations, as is always the case with WayForward;
- Great soundtrack by Jake Kaufman (other Shantae games, Mighty Switch Force, Shovel Knight);
- Lots of variety in every aspect, from enemies to levels to music to gameplay mechanics.

Cons:
- Initially feels a bit limited, takes a bit of time to really get going (although never to the point of boredom for me personally);
- Some people might not like old-school backtracking (e.g. you get an item--now you must find which previously met NPC to show it to);
- Wacky writing occasionally feels a bit dumb rather than silly, but that's rare and mostly in the beginning;
- High-res character portraits and fonts clash awfully and quite inexcusably with pixel-painted graphics;
- Post-game / good ending stuff can get a tad tiresome, although the true final boss is satisfying enough.

All in all: despite the stuff listed as flaws, it's one of the best games in the action/adventure (metroidvania") genre. Get this game and play it

